<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. An Account of Lake Superior, 1807-1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0037</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">and I have no reason to doubt his veracity, is a phenomenon that will give ample matter of discussion to the Zoologists.  Some days march nearer Lake Superior, one of them caught a Beaver with two tails, the lesser springing from the root of the larger or natural tail, which is a lusus nature never before heard of here.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">I write this the 21<sup>st</sup> March 1809 and hope to have the specimens of the former and last mentioned skins by the middle of May next.  The greatest quantity of fish resort to the large rivers of Lake Superior during the proper season.  Every Spring Vessels might be laden with the finest Sturgeon from Keeywaynan and Natanagan Rivers alone<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  In those of the North, red and white Trout equally abound every Autumn.</p>
